nian-Armenian Marches in the 12th Century and David of Gandzak (c. 1065-1140) -- t15A The Gate of Ganja -- t16 Reverse Engineering: A State-Created "Albanian Apostolic Church" -- tGeneral References -- tIndexes0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aBy consequence of the Karabakh War in 2020 and due to Azerbaijanian revisionism concerning the history, culture and cultural monuments of the region, the discussion on Caucasian "Albania", which is little known in the West in both academic and public circles, has been reignited. The handbook provides an overview of the current state of research on the Caucasian "Albanians" in an objective, scientifically sound manner. The contributions are not necessarily intended to reveal new scientific findings but rather to summarise approved knowledge. The volume brings together internationally renowned scholars, researchers and practitioners from various fields of studies reporting on and reviewing the state of research concerning the Caucasian "Albanians", their history and archaeology, their language and written monuments, their religion, church history and their art, including their relation to the Udi people of today. The companion is intended to neutrally introduce the readership to the subject of Caucasian Albania from various perspectives.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aKaukasisches Albanien. 4aSüdkaukasus. 4aÖstlich-orthodoxe Kirchen. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aCaucasian Albania.  aCaucasian Albanian Language.  aEastern Orthodoxy.  aSouthern Caucasus.1 aBais, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4